	abstract = {Most mutualisms vary in outcome along a continuum from strong mutualism to commensalism or even parasitism, driven by the interaction’s abiotic and biotic context. This variation can have far-reaching consequences, influencing the ecological stability and evolutionary trajectory of mutualisms. Despite its potential importance, many key questions about context dependency remain unanswered for most major mutualisms. Studies on context dependency are distributed very unevenly among the world’s major types of mutualisms, with many more studies on mycorrhizae, rhizobial symbiosis, and plant–pollinator interactions, compared to other major mutualisms such as corals, grasses and fungal endophytes, insects and their protective symbiotic bacteria, and cleaner fish and their clients. Four key research tools are described that can be used to explore context dependency in mutualisms: models, field observational studies, manipulative experiments, and meta-analyses. Eight key questions on context dependency in mutualisms are articulated, and research is highlighted that has applied the four tools to answer these questions. The questions address how mutualisms change in outcome with abiotic environmental gradients, community context, population densities, and genetic variation, and are articulated in a manner that aims to inspire a search for general principles of context dependency in mutualisms.},
